<font color="#FF0000">KIM PHUC AND FALSE G.I.GUILT</font><br>
<tt>Wed Dec 17 15:22:58 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
From Hacworth.com newsletter 12-15-97:<br>
          THE MYTH OF THE GIRL IN THE PHOTO<br><br>
Most Americans recall the bombing of a village in Vietnam, with the naked and terrified little girl running toward the Pulitzer Prize-winning photographer. The shocking photo was published with a heart-wrenching story, but if a picture speaks a thousand words, most of the words associated with this photo are false or misleading.<br><br>
The impression is given that it was an American or &quot;American ordered&quot; attack. As stated by the photographer himself, and shown on film, the Vietnam Air Force (VNAF) dropped the bombs, as reported at the time by noted correspondent Peter Arnett.<br><br>
The battle in June of 1972, was an all-Vietnamese fight, with the Army of the Republic of Vietnam (ARVN) fighting the North Vietnamese Army (NVA), and requesting support from their own air force. Vietnamese were fighting Vietnamese at Trang Bang, and when Kim Phuc was burned, it was they who called for help from Vietnamese flown aircraft. Even the photographer was Vietnamese, although he later became a US citizen.<br><br>
The fighters were hitting NVA positions outside the village, when Kim and others, including ARVN soldiers, ran from a pagoda and away from the village. The pilot of a Vietnamese fighter saw the people running toward ARVN positions, and dove to attack, as reported by eyewitness UPI television correspondent Christopher Wain. It was an all-Vietnamese fight, conducted and controlled by Vietnamese.<br><br>
The myth continues because it is a dramatic photo, and because the handlers of the woman whom the little girl has become, arranged for her to go to the Vietnam Veterans' Memorial on Veteran's Day of 1996, &quot;to forgive&quot;. She came to our nation's capital, to offer forgiveness to a nation and the men who did not burn her, but even that would have been a one-time story, if not for a man who has inserted himself into the tragedy.<br><br>
The Reverend John Plummer, a Methodist minister claimed that day that, &quot;I am the one.&quot; With his published and televised claims to be the man who ordered the strike against the village, and his story of salvation to become a minister, he has almost replaced Kim Phuc as the central figure in the myth. It would seem that it is not for lack of trying on his part. &quot;I am the one responsible for the agony of the little girl.&quot; &quot;I ordered the bombing.&quot; &quot;I'm sorry. I'm so sorry.&quot;<br><br>
His message of peace and forgiveness plays well to the American willingness to forgive and forget. During the year since he came forward to grasp responsibility for something he could not have done, this minister of a small country church has addressed more people than he had addressed in his entire life, prior to that day at The Wall. His public claims have given him a sort of celebrity status within the church, and he is in demand as a speaker for his &quot;ministry of forgiveness&quot;.<br><br>
His claims of involvement in &quot;ordering&quot; Vietnamese aircraft to strike have been thoroughly refuted by the officer in charge of his staff section, and by the former commander of his unit. Both of these men continued to be promoted, and retired as General Officers with five stars between them, while the staff officer was eliminated from the Army while still a captain. Introduced in recent reports as the &quot;American commander who ordered the attack&quot;, he now says he will use more care with his words in the future. Unable to support his claim to have ordered the attack, he now says he used the term &quot;ordered&quot; interchangeably with &quot;coordinated&quot;. His superiors say he was not even in a position to coordinate such an action. They say he was 80 kilometers from the fight, in one of the most minor positions on the staff, with absolute no authority to direct any such activity.<br><br>
Personal guilt is something borne sooner by some than others, and few deny the minister's right to feel whatever personal responsibility he might care to feel. We should all remember that personal responsibility entails a personal forgiveness, and not a contrived public confession and marketing of a ministry that implies that this Myth is true.<br><br>
-- Another One of the Troops
